## ðŸŒ¦ï¸ What we *know* about December pressure pattern over BoB

* During Octoberâ€“December, climatological mean sea-level pressure (MSLP) patterns over the Bay of Bengal show a **low-pressure area drifting southwards** over the central/southern BoB. By December, this low tends to lie closer to the equator. ([Mausam][1])
* Meanwhile, a â€œhigh-pressure areaâ€ develops over the northern part of the Indian subcontinent (linked to winter continental high-pressure systems, e.g., the Siberian High). This juxtaposition â€” low pressure in south BoB, high pressure inland/north â€” produces a **northâ€“south pressure gradient** over Bay of Bengal + adjoining land-sea region. ([Mausam][1])
* The isobars (lines of equal pressure) during December tend to run roughly **parallel to the equator** over BoB, implying that the dominant pressure gradient is meridional (northâ€“south), not zonal (eastâ€“west). ([Mausam][2])
* This meridional gradient supports the typical **northeasterly / easterly surface winds** over the Bay during Novemberâ€“December. ([Mausam][1])

So climatologically, in â€œnormalâ€ December conditions, the pressure gradient over BoB is from relatively higher pressure to the north (or over the landmass) down towards lower pressure over the southern BoB â€” driving winds roughly from north â†’ south (on the sea surface), often modified by Coriolis to give easterly/northeasterly flows.

