---

## ðŸ”­ What climatology says about December pressure patterns over Bay of Bengal

Based on long-term (1979â€“2021) climatology compiled by India Meteorological Department (IMD) using ERA5 data:

* By December the â€œlow-pressure areaâ€ over the Bay shifts southwards â€” typically close to the equator. ([Mausam][3])
* Simultaneously, a continental high-pressure zone (linked to winter high over northern India / Asia) tends to strengthen. This sets up a **meridional pressure gradient** (higher over the north/land, lower over southern BoB). ([Mausam][3])
* The isobars (lines of equal pressure) over Bay of Bengal during December are often nearly **parallel to the equator** â€” indicating that the dominant pressure gradient (and hence surface wind forcing) tends to be roughly **northâ€“south** (i.e. from north â†’ south). ([Mausam][3])
* This pattern is why winter / post-monsoon winds over the Bay tend to be **easterlies / northeasterlies** â€” consistent with northerly pressure forcing + Earthâ€™s rotation (Coriolis). ([Mausam][3])

Hence, climatologically, you expect a **southward-directed pressure gradient** over much of the Bay in December (higher values to the north, lower to the south).

